<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=17293&amp;p=217570#p217570</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=17293&amp;p=217570#p217570"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Getting the best-sounding samples]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=17293&amp;p=217570#p217570"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />...or ere you just saying to try a lower target samplerate to see if it sounds better? (It's that you specifically suggested to pitch it up before importing that throws me here... why not just import at the samplerate you want it to be played at?)<br /></div><br /><br />Yeah you could do either and the result should be 1:1 provided the export itself has a high enough sample rate. With a pitch shift up and a low output samplerate, you eventually start to push harmonic content outside the window if you go high enough = aliasing and low pass filtering. Of course, if you go low enough with the sample rate only, you get the same result. <br /><br />It is better (more controlled) to condition the sample with EQ:s / filters beforehand, at any rate.<br /><br />I agree setting just setting the sample rate is more straightforward. I just got used to a method where a sample in audacity is shifted by the count of semitones, and then account for that later.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=7508">FrankenGraphics</a> — Thu Apr 26, 2018 9:25 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
